<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06028147 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06028147 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  PROFESSIONAL; FOOTBALL; CHAMPIONSHIP; GAME; NEWS; BRIEF  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  A compilation of excerpts from writers covering the Super Bowl:;   GIANTS KEEPIT SIMPLE  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  WHAT OTHERS ARE SAYING  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     You can have your no-huddles. You can have your sugar huddle. You can haveyour mind-bending offensive schemes, so complicated as to befuddle an MITgraduate.;    While the war takes on aspects of a high-stakes Nintendo game,football, at least as the Giants practice it, remains a ground affair, brutalin its simplicity and power. Nothing fancy here.;    The Giants, who stillsubscribe to the ancient notion that a huddle is a necessary thing, simplyplayed keep-away.; -- Bob Kravitz; Rocky Mountain News;  WORLD OF ISOLATION;   In the wake of the war, maybe there is something to be said for going on withthe game.;    Tampa Stadium on Sunday was an isolated world. There were noradios and no portable television sets allowed in, so spectators couldn't keepup with developments in the war.;    Only the men and women who did securitysearches, and the long line of those to be searched, and the helicoptersoverhead reminded everyone that there was more than a football game involvedhere -- or, that is, that there might be something more important somewherethan a football game.; -- Ira Berkow; New York Times;  WORTH THE WAIT;    Itwas worth waiting for.;    At a time when we needed it most, at a time whenmaybe we felt an occasional stab of guilt about having fun, at a time when wewere not quite sure whether it was OK to forget about Scuds and that purposelyloosed black tide of crude, the Giants and Bills gave us a corker.;    -- BillLyon; Philadelphia Inquirer;  THEATRICAL ENDING;    The Super Bowl, of course,isn't merely another pro football game. It's a prime-time spectacle for theNFL and television networks.;    In the beginning, each team tried to do whatit does best: a no-huddle offense by the Bills, a no-touchdown defense by theGiants.;    In the end, Scott Norwood's missed 47-yard field-goal attemptprovided one of the most theatrical finishes in all 25 Super Bowl games.; --Dave Anderson; New York Times;  A GIANT OFFENSIVE;    The Giants wereseven-point underdogs because of the Bills' awesome offense. Everyone knew theGiants could play great defense, but few thought their offense was strongenough to win.;    As it turned out, a game ball should have gone to Giantsoffensive coordinator Ron Erhardt, a man ignored all week by a media crowdeager to talk with Buffalo offensive coordinator Ted Marchibroda.; -- JerryGreene; Orlando Sentinel;  CRUCIAL FIRST SERIES;    The first series of thegame was crucial. The Giants needed to know they could stop the Bills, andthey did -- three downs and out.;    -- Rams Coach John Robinson; For theAssociated Press  </TEXT><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910128  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Monday  </DAY><MONTH>  January  </MONTH><PG.COL>  6E  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  459  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Monday January 28, 199100028147,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>